    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.36a.69"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">69</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        4 350 East 56th Place, Tulsa, Ok-74135
                        October 25th 1972.
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>5835 Vine, Lincoln, Nebraska.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I have postponed my writing to tell you how much I have enjoyed All Is But a Beginning and I think the principal reason was that I felt unable to express it adequately.  I am tempted to say it is the best you have done; certainly it is equal to the best and it certainly proves that the Divine Fire survives the years.  I enjoyed the story of the hardships of growing up told simply and without any whining about poverty. I thunk you must have had a wonderful mother as well.</p> 
                
                <p>I liked most of all your <hi rend="underline">thoughts</hi> shared with the reader for what a man thinks must be far more important than what has happened to him. The finale,All is But a Beginning, is one of the finest th<del/><add>i</add>ngs I have ever read and I hope to get much more of your Credo in the forthcoming volume..  I remember too your "meditation place" or altar on the hill above Branson, Missouri and how much I appreciated being admitted to it.</p>
                
                <p>How I would enjoy an opportunity to visit with you again or even to hear more about the children and grandchildren; I remember Sigurd but Hilda I felt I really knew.  <hi rend="underline">But</hi>, with the beauty of this first volume and the promise of a forthcoming second there is a real urgency that none of your friends distract you f<del>o</del><add>r</add>om your appointed task.  I would not ask an answer; rather I would conserve your energies for the major task and my supplications shall include the plea that you may be spared in good health for such a time as is needed to needed to finish and polish to your exacting standards the other book.</p>
                
                <p>I just phoned Lewis<del>h</del> Meyer and was informed that he carries All is But a Beginning in stock; I am hoping he will review it on <hi rend="caps">TV</hi> soon.</p> 
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely your f<del>i</del><add>r</add>iend and admirer</salute>
                    
                    <signed>W O Cralle</signed>
                    <signed>Walter O. Cralle</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript>
                    <opener><hi rend="caps">P.S.</hi></opener> <p>Ms Hall sent me some trading stamps which are not usable here in Tulsa; perhaps Mrs. Young could use them.</p> <closer><signed>WOC.</signed></closer> 
                </postscript>
                
                <fw>2</fw>
                
            </div1>
